== 註釋 ==
{{Portal box|教育}}
{{cnote|a|The school was called a seminary but did not engage in religious instruction. It was part finishing school and part preparatory school, designed to produce female teachers.{{sfn|Cubbage|2009|p=91}} The four-year program (which the Junior College later extended to six) covered what was essentially a good quality high school program, such that "students [were] prepared for the very best institutions east and west."<ref>{{cite book | page = 717 | chapter = The Frances Shimer School of the University of Chicago | title = Historical Encyclopedia of Illinois and History of Carroll County | volume = II | editor1-last = Bateman | editor1-first=Newton | editor2-last=Selby | editor2-first = Paul | editor3-last = Hostetter | editor3-first = Charles L. | location = Chicago | publisher = Munsell Pub. Co. | year = 1913  | oclc = 1745414}}</ref>}}
{{cnote|b| Under the agreement, Shimer remained independent with its own board, of which a majority represented the U. of C. and two-thirds were required to be Baptist. Shimer was administered locally, but subject to a chief administrator in Chicago for final decisions.{{sfn|Moorhead|1983|p=47}}}}
{{cnote |c| The others are St. John's College, U.S.|St. John's College in [[Annapolis,_Maryland|Annapolis, Maryland]], and Santa Fe, New Mexico, Thomas Aquinas College in Santa Paula, California, and Thomas More College of Liberal Arts in Merrimack, New Hampshire.<ref name = smallcampus>{{cite news | title = Small Campus, Big Books | last = Johnson | first = Dirk | date = 2007-11-04 | newspaper = The New York Times |url =  http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/education/edlife/shimer.html | accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref>}}
{{cnote|d|Adler and Hutchins collaborated on ''The Great Books of the Western World'', published in 1952, which was intended to present the entire Western canon in one 54 volume set.<ref>{{cite book | page =297 | title = Robert Maynard Hutchins: A Memoir | last = Mayer | first = Milton S. | location = Berkeley, CA | publisher = University of California Press | year = 1993 | isbn = 052007091}}</ref> The selection of works it contained defined the reading list on which Great Books curricula were based, and which Shimer has largely kept, with minor changes, ever since.}}
{{cnote|e|The Hutchins plan also instituted placement exams, which students would take before enrollment "to determine how much or how little of the program they need".<ref>{{cite book | title = Chicago's Left Bank | url = https://archive.org/details/chicagosleftbank00smit | page = [https://archive.org/details/chicagosleftbank00smit/page/236 236] | last = Smith | first = Jesse Alan | location = Chicago | publisher = H. Regnery Co. | year = 1953 | oclc = 1072972}}</ref> This practice lives on at Shimer, where students are able to place out of several of the basic core courses by examination.{{sfn|Shimer College Catalog|2009|p=15}}
}}
{{cnote|f|This aspirational goal is very rarely achieved. Professor David Shiner, who joined the faculty in 1977, received special recognition from the college in 1998 for the "unique distinction of having taught the entire core curriculum".<ref>{{cite web | title = David Shiner, Professor of Humanities and the History of Ideas | publisher = Shimer College | url = http://www.shimer.edu/aboutshimercollege/DavidShiner.cfm | accessdate = 2010-05-10 | archive-date = 2010-11-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101129110252/http://shimer.edu/aboutshimercollege/DavidShiner.cfm | dead-url = yes }}</ref>}}

